#. type: Plain text
#: en/user_basics.ssi:379
msgid "2~webbooting Webbooting"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/user_basics.ssi:381
msgid ""
"Webbooting is a convenient way of retrieving and booting live systems using "
"the internet as a means. The requirements for webbooting are very few. On "
"the one hand, you need a medium with a bootloader, an initial ramdisk and a "
"kernel. On the other hand, a web server to store the squashfs files which "
"contain the filesystem."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/user_basics.ssi:383
msgid "3~ Getting the webboot files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/user_basics.ssi:385
msgid ""
"As usual, you can build the images yourself or use the pre-built files, "
"which are available on the project's homepage at http://live-systems.org/. "
"Using pre-built images would be handy for doing initial testing until one "
"can fine tune their own needs. If you have built a live image you will find "
"the files needed for webbooting in the build directory under #{binary/live/}"
"#. The files are called #{vmlinuz}#, #{initrd.img}# and #{filesystem."
"squashfs}#."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/user_basics.ssi:387
msgid "3~ Booting webboot images"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/user_basics.ssi:389
msgid ""
"While some users will use virtualization to test webbooting, we use real "
"hardware here to match the following possible use case which should only be "
"considered as an example."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/user_basics.ssi:391
msgid ""
"In order to boot a webboot image it is enough to have the components "
"mentioned above in a usb stick and install syslinux as bootloader. Then boot "
"from the usb stick and type #{fetch=URL/PATH/TO/FILE}# at the boot options. "
"live-boot will retrieve the squashfs file and store it into ram. This way, "
"it is possible to use the downloaded compressed filesystem like a regular "
"live system. For example:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/user_basics.ssi:395
#, no-wrap
msgid " append boot=live components fetch=http://192.168.2.50/images/webboot/filesystem.squashfs\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/user_basics.ssi:398
#, no-wrap
msgid "*{Use case:}* You have a web server in which you have stored two squashfs images, one which contains a desktop, like for example gnome, and a rescue one. If you need a graphical environment for one machine, you can plug your usb stick in and webboot the gnome image. If you need rescue tools included in the second type of image, for another machine, you can webboot the rescue one.\n"
msgstr ""
